Dense irregular CT is largely made up of collagen type I fibres arranged in a meshwork sheet;  imparts tensile strength in >1 direction.  Dense irregular CT has relatively little GS, relatively fewer cells and cell types; cells that are present are largely fibroblasts.
Dense irregular CT forms: reticular layer of dermis of skin (below), periosteum, perichondrium, organ capsules, joint capsules, submucosa of GI tract

Underlying the stratified squamous keratinized epithelium of our skin is the dermis. It includes a layer of dense irregular CT. Its coarse bundles of collagen type I fibres run in all directions. This creates a tough layer deep to our skin that withstands stretch in all directions.

In the picture on the left, bundles of collagen type I fibres are seen to run in and out of the plane of section.
